00:57:18.795 --> 00:57:24.144
Incoming livestream: So you have your sensors, very innocuous layer, just gathers information.

39
00:57:24.555 --> 00:57:26.694
Incoming livestream: Then you have the perceiving layer.

40
00:57:29.955 --> 00:57:44.284
Incoming livestream: You can see it better here. Yeah, the perception layer is making sense of the sensors, figuring out what are all these sensors, because of course, there could be sensors which are spoofed, sensors which are incorrect. It has to figure out which are the right sensors, and how do you…

41
00:57:44.445 --> 00:57:50.125
Incoming livestream: Understand the correlation between all the sensor data, Then comes the world model.

42
00:57:51.075 --> 00:57:56.805
Incoming livestream: Here, in this case, if you think of, we're going to pick up a coffee cup from the table.

43
00:57:57.305 --> 00:57:58.865
Incoming livestream: So, here.

44
00:57:59.125 --> 00:58:11.874
Incoming livestream: The cup is, sitting on a table. The world models actually figures out what is the amount of… what kind of cup is it, where do you grasp the cup so that the coffee doesn't spill.

45
00:58:11.975 --> 00:58:24.315
Incoming livestream: Is the cup fragile or not? Is the desk… is a soft surface or a hard surface, etc. That is the world model. It looks and perceives the state of the world at that time.

46
00:58:26.215 --> 00:58:34.155
Incoming livestream: And that, predicts what… what action should I take, and what will be the outcome of whatever action I take. That is the world model.

47
00:58:35.335 --> 00:58:38.755
Incoming livestream: And from, basically, the world model is now looking at

48
00:58:39.435 --> 00:58:53.884
Incoming livestream: this is, basically, should I grip it? If it's a fragile cup, I need to grip it very gently. If it is, you know, paper cups versus a ceramic cup, etc. If it has a handle or not, etc. All that is determined in this layer.

49
00:58:56.345 --> 00:58:57.514
Incoming livestream: There you go.

50
00:58:57.745 --> 00:58:59.165
Incoming livestream: cup gets lifted.

51
00:58:59.515 --> 00:59:07.605
Incoming livestream: But if the prediction is wrong in this model, the cup is… you'll spill. You'll spill the coffee cup, because you're holding it wrong.

52
00:59:10.735 --> 00:59:19.004
Incoming livestream: So then, of course, the LLMs, they reason and plan out the course of action, so that that… those sequence of actions will be given to the robot.

53
00:59:21.345 --> 00:59:31.975
Incoming livestream: And of course, the VLA tells, you know, what kind of robot it is, and what is a… how many inches of whatever the arm has to move, etc, and at what angle, etc.

54
00:59:32.415 --> 00:59:36.785
Incoming livestream: And that's when you move the coffee cup correctly. You can lift up the coffee cup.

55
00:59:37.385 --> 00:59:40.795
Incoming livestream: So all of these layers have to work in conjunction.

56
00:59:41.555 --> 00:59:49.535
Incoming livestream: Again, we'll talk about this as soon as we go deeper into this talk, we'll see that, you know, where the responsibility lies.

57
00:59:49.774 --> 00:59:54.905
Incoming livestream: Who is the final Which is the final layer that controls all of this.

58
00:59:58.484 --> 01:00:00.554
Incoming livestream: So, let's see what can go wrong.

59
01:00:00.835 --> 01:00:19.145
Incoming livestream: I think many of us have been in these situations, in the older days, where the GPS is telling, make a U-turn, make a U-turn, make a U-turn. It's giving you advice, it is not giving you permission, right? It doesn't know anything about the physical world. It is just saying, you need to make a U-turn, you have missed your exit, right?

60
01:00:19.335 --> 01:00:34.215
Incoming livestream: It's here, it's up to the human being to get into that loop and figure out whether it is safe to make the action. Today, of course, there are some hardware sensors which say, okay, we can't take that action, and you'll delay the action, which is fine.

61
01:00:35.335 --> 01:00:37.375
Incoming livestream: Then there are other ways that…

62
01:00:37.524 --> 01:00:47.115
Incoming livestream: things can go wrong in physical AI is, of course, if somebody spoofs, or has a… if there is a security attack.

63
01:00:47.285 --> 01:01:04.824
Incoming livestream: So basically, these… both systems are unsafe, right? One is unsafe, it'll fail accidentally, like making a U-turn, whereas the secure, you know, injecting security vulnerability attacks, all that makes the system fail intentionally.

64
01:01:05.984 --> 01:01:12.524
Incoming livestream: And that's why we need a fail-safe architecture. We'll get into how to build an architecture like that for physical AI systems.

65
01:01:14.165 --> 01:01:21.925
Incoming livestream: Now, there's one other aspect, which is there in physical AI, That is not covered anywhere.

66
01:01:22.505 --> 01:01:24.435
Incoming livestream: And that is latency.

67
01:01:25.405 --> 01:01:38.435
Incoming livestream: So far, when we see LLMs, etc, remember LLMs started with a 7 billion model, or a 10, 15 million parameter model, and they went up to 405 million parameters.

68
01:01:38.575 --> 01:01:44.314
Incoming livestream: Similarly, the context window started at 4K, 32K, 128, and a 1 million context window.

69
01:01:45.335 --> 01:01:50.235
Incoming livestream: LLMs were scaling with the size of the model. VLAs don't scale with that.

70
01:01:50.365 --> 01:01:56.294
Incoming livestream: We… for VLAs, It is the latency and the control which is most important.

71
01:01:57.115 --> 01:02:04.485
Incoming livestream: And LLMs, Because latency is such an important criteria here for physical systems, LLMs can…

72
01:02:04.625 --> 01:02:17.845
