95
01:05:08.155 --> 01:05:16.565
Incoming livestream: Humans can decide, plan, everything before. That means they create the intent, but they cannot actually be in the execution path.

96
01:05:19.405 --> 01:05:22.224
Incoming livestream: So, lots of things can go wrong, right?

97
01:05:22.665 --> 01:05:32.185
Incoming livestream: You can have, but what fail-safe architecture will do is answer how how to control

98
01:05:32.465 --> 01:05:41.285
Incoming livestream: how to reduce these errors. So, you can have physical kill paths, right? You can have override buttons, you can degrade the performance of the system.

99
01:05:41.465 --> 01:05:56.854
Incoming livestream: So that it fails more gracefully. That's very much in the reliability space that, you know, systems don't fail abruptly, but they degrade gracefully, etc. And you have deterministic control paths, you can have boundary latency, all of these techniques are there.

100
01:05:59.385 --> 01:06:04.525
Incoming livestream: But that's where… this is the fail-safe architecture. So, fail-safe architecture, you can put all of this.

101
01:06:05.445 --> 01:06:06.924
Incoming livestream: Who decides all this?

102
01:06:08.615 --> 01:06:18.955
Incoming livestream: Who decides what the limits are, who decides what are the control paths, and who decides when to override that switch, or when to pull the plug on the, system?

103
01:06:19.405 --> 01:06:27.285
